Do you have any idea what could have been the problem with these resources? Read-only, target not writable?

We should make sure that we first rename the resource, then update all references, But I guess this is already the case, Markus?

> We should make sure that we first rename the resource, then update all
> references, But I guess this is already the case, Markus?

No, generally, we update all files and only move them afterwards. Changing this would be difficult and would not solve the underlying problem.

M.H.: The dialog said:
'Click "Undo" to undo all successfully executed changes of the current refactoring. Click "Abort" to abort the current refactoring.'

If you click "Abort" in this situation, eclipse just gives up and leaves everything in the partially-refactored state. "Undo" would likely have correctly undone the changes in the other files.

If the problem was really that another application has a write lock on the file, then we can't do much, since java.io.File has no query to find out whether such a lock exists.

I filed bug 126372 for better handling of such cases (make Undo the default and/or allow Undo after pressing Abort).

Closing as wontfix. If the problem was not that another application had locked the file, then please reopen and provide steps to reproduce.
